			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2021</a> paper:</span><br><i>Vision: the next 700 language workbenches</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MikhailBarash.html">Mikhail Barash</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3486608.3486907">10.1145/3486608.3486907</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The paper’s core contribution is tooling/infrastructure for language engineering (e.g., IDE/editor support).
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> It emphasizes modularity/composition/integration (embedding or coordinating language components).
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2c.html"><span class="tagL">T2C: Variability</span></a><ul><li> It targets product lines/variability (feature models, variability, configuration).
</li></ul></li></ul>
